1. ping: Is a command to check if there is data transfer/receive on an instance/server/website
E.g. ubuntu@ip-172-$ping trainwithshubham.com
This shows your internet is working and the website is up

2. netstat (Network statistics) - Used to active internet connection
$ sudo apt install net-tools
$ netstat
# Will give all network tcp related information

3. ifconfig (interface configuration)
Shows all networks like docker network, gives network interface card (nic)

4. traceroute vs tracepath
Traceroute and tracepath are network diagnostic tools used to trace the path packets take to a destination,
with traceroute providing detailed hop information and tracepath offering a simpler view with MTU insights.

$ sudo apt install traceroute
$ traceroute youtube.com     #this will all the routes hopped to access the website youtube.com

All the commands tell the latency (seconds taken for connection on the server)

5. mtr (my trace route) - combines traceroute and path and gives shorter/brief information.

6. nslookup - Gives server public (usually ipv4) and private ip(usually ipv6) address and the ip address you were trying to ping like trainwithshubham.com alongwith its ip address and also ip address for name.

7. telnet - Does the samething, only difference you can provide port number as well. Helps connect to port
E.g. telnet trainwithshubham.com 80
443 is secure vs 80 is public

8. hostname
Gives the ip address 
$cat /etc/hosts #will give all the host names

9. ip
$ ip address shows
#This will all the ip addresses you have

10. iwconfig - internet of wireless network config
$ sudo apt install wireless tools.
$ iwconfig      #will show all wireless attachments on this terminal/ec2 instance

Check iwconfig on both local and remote (ec2 instance)terminal. 
11. ss - A version of netstat

12. arp (address resolution protocol) - The arp (Address Resolution Protocol) command is a networking tool used to display and modify 
the ARP cache, which maps IP addresses to physical MAC addresses on a local network. It is used for troubleshooting network connectivity, 
identifying connected devices, and managing static entries.


